<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-317-346  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 317 346.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  May 29 1989 v6 n21 p17(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>PC local net decisions fall on corporate shoulders; standardizingnetwork purchases is the goal.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>DiDio, Laura.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The purchasing of local area networks (LANs) is being done at highlevels in many corporations.andP;  Decisions which used to be in therealm of the department heads are being made by high-levelexecutives, as corporations try to get an edge on the competitionwith strategic LANs.andP;  Standardization and compatibility is more ofa concern as LANs and WANs become integral to business strategy.andO;Information is needed on the corporate scale as well as inindividual departments, and corporate executives have realizedthat centralized LAN acquisition is the best strategy forsupporting corporate-wide communication.andP;  Corporate executivescontrol 65 percent of network purchases in the insurance sector,59 percent in banking, and 50 percent in the medical industry.andO;Individual departments are usually required to pay for LANpurchases.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Local Area NetworksPurchasesDecision MakingCompaniesSurveyStandardizationCompetitionStrategic Planning.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Who buys the LAN? (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>